ℹ Please use `gather()` instead.
ℹ The deprecated feature was likely used in the ggfortify package.
  Please report the issue at <https://github.com/sinhrks/ggfortify/issues>.
```
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("mtcars")
learner = lrn("regr.glmnet")
learner$train(task)

autoplot(learner)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


## Rpart

The classifcation tree of an rpart learner can be plotted.
We have to fit the learner with `keep_model = TRUE` to keep the model object.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("penguins")
learner = lrn("classif.rpart", keep_model = TRUE)
learner$train(task)

autoplot(learner)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


We can also plot regression trees.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("mtcars")
learner = lrn("regr.rpart", keep_model = TRUE)
learner$train(task)

autoplot(learner)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


## ClustHierachical

The `"dend"` plot shows the result of hierarchical clustering of the data.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(mlr3cluster)

task = tsk("usarrests")
learner = lrn("clust.hclust")
learner$train(task)

autoplot(learner, type = "dend", task = task)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"scree"` type plots the number of clusters and the height.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(learner, type = "scree")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


# Prediction

## Classification

We plot the predictions of a classification learner.
The `"stacked"` plot shows the predicted and true class labels.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("spam")
learner = lrn("classif.rpart", predict_type = "prob")
pred = learner$train(task)$predict(task)

autoplot(pred, type = "stacked")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-14-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The ROC curve plots the true positive rate against the false positive rate at different thresholds.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, type = "roc")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::



The precision-recall curve plots the precision against the recall at different thresholds.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, type = "prc")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-16-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"threshold"` plot varies the threshold of a binary classification and plots against the resulting performance.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, type = "threshold")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


## Regression

The predictions of a regression learner are often presented as a scatterplot of truth and predicted response.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("boston_housing")
learner = lrn("regr.rpart")
pred = learner$train(task)$predict(task)

autoplot(pred, type = "xy")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-18-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


Additionally, plot the response with the residuals.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, type = "residual")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


We can also plot the distribution of the residuals.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, type = "histogram", binwidth = 1)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
```
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-20-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


## Cluster

The predictions of a cluster learner are often presented as a scatterplot of the data points colored by the cluster.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(mlr3cluster)

task = tsk("usarrests")
learner = lrn("clust.kmeans", centers = 3)
pred = learner$train(task)$predict(task)

autoplot(pred, task, type = "scatter")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-21-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"sil"` plot shows the silhouette width of the clusters.
The dashed line is the mean silhouette width.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, task, type = "sil")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-22-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"pca"` plot shows the first two principal components of the data colored by the cluster.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(pred, task, type = "pca")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-23-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


# Resample Result

## Classification

The `"boxplot"` shows the distribution of the performance measures.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("sonar")
learner = lrn("classif.rpart", predict_type = "prob")
resampling = rsmp("cv")
rr = resample(task, learner, resampling)

autoplot(rr, type = "boxplot")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-24-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


We can also plot the distribution of the performance measures as a "`histogram`".


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(rr, type = "histogram", bins = 30)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
```
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-25-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The ROC curve plots the true positive rate against the false positive rate at different thresholds.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(rr, type = "roc")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-26-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The precision-recall curve plots the precision against the recall at different thresholds.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
autoplot(rr, type = "prc")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-27-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"prediction"` plot shows two features and the predicted class in the background.
Points mark the observations of the test set and the color presents the truth.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("pima")
task$filter(seq(100))
task$select(c("age", "glucose"))
learner = lrn("classif.rpart")
resampling = rsmp("cv", folds = 3)
rr = resample(task, learner, resampling, store_models = TRUE)

autoplot(rr, type = "prediction")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-28-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


Alternatively, we can plot class probabilities.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("pima")
task$filter(seq(100))
task$select(c("age", "glucose"))
learner = lrn("classif.rpart", predict_type = "prob")
resampling = rsmp("cv", folds = 3)
rr = resample(task, learner, resampling, store_models = TRUE)

autoplot(rr, type = "prediction")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-29-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


In addition to the test set, we can also plot the train set.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("pima")
task$filter(seq(100))
task$select(c("age", "glucose"))
learner = lrn("classif.rpart", predict_type = "prob", predict_sets = c("train", "test"))
resampling = rsmp("cv", folds = 3)
rr = resample(task, learner, resampling, store_models = TRUE)

autoplot(rr, type = "prediction", predict_sets = c("train", "test"))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-30-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


The `"prediction"` plot can also show categorical features.


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
task = tsk("german_credit")
task$filter(seq(100))
task$select(c("housing", "employment_duration"))
learner = lrn("classif.rpart")
resampling = rsmp("cv", folds = 3)
rr = resample(task, learner, resampling, store_models = TRUE)

autoplot(rr, type = "prediction")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-31-1.png){fig-align='center' width=672}
:::
:::


## Regression

The "`prediction`" plot shows one feature and the response.
Points mark the observations of the test set.


